                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="19454" author="balex" created="Thu, 7 Sep 2006 14:35:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What is wrong with using AccessDeniedHandler and the associated AccessDeniedHandlerImpl? These were added expressly for maintaining the SecurityContextHolder whilst rendering an error view.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19469" author="rolfarne" created="Thu, 7 Sep 2006 22:41:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;To illustrate the issue I used a security related scenario (403), and in such cases I could use AccessDeniedHandlerImpl.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, I am looking for a general solution where any kind of application exceptions (like user input errors) are trapped by the servlet container (after Acegi filter has finished its job) and directed to an &apos;error page handler&apos;. In such cases the securtiy context is cleared, and you would like to restore the security context again.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19648" author="balex" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 19:29:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I looked at you approach and it looks good.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Would it be possible to provide a patch against current SVN HEAD that introduces this behaviour to HttpSessionContextIntegrationFilter? The main issue with once-per-request handling is when RequestDispatchers are being used to do things like SiteMesh decorate a page.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19649" author="balex" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 19:30:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is actually a feature improvement, not a bug in the existing implementation (as it does not claim to provide this capability). I am open to including it in 1.0.2 if we can get a patch in time, but otherwise we&apos;ll need to put it into 1.1.0.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19816" author="balex" created="Fri, 22 Sep 2006 17:23:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Moved to 1.0.3, as it is not a bug and no patch has been provided as yet.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20043" author="felipeal" created="Wed, 4 Oct 2006 03:00:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Ben,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here is another scenario where such information is useful.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have an aplication which uses Struts and Tiles (and Acegi, of course &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;. The layout has a left menu whose links are enabled according to the roles of the logged user. If I configure web.xml to forward error 404 for such page, the request has no roles and hence no menu item is shown (on the other had, if I access the page directly, everything works fine).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;#8211; Felipe&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20746" author="balex" created="Sun, 12 Nov 2006 06:58:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Moved to 1.1.0 as this is not a bug and no patch has been provided to introduce this new feature.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="22973" author="youngm" created="Fri, 30 Mar 2007 06:27:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Here is a patch that fixed the problem for me.  It would be nice if this could make it into 1.0.4&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="23890" author="pascalalberty" created="Mon, 21 May 2007 22:18:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Also useful if your error pages are decorated and contain menus depending on roles&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="23955" author="balex" created="Wed, 23 May 2007 13:05:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch applied to SVN; tests still pass; SVN revision 1858.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="126106" author="issuemaster" created="Sat, 6 Feb 2016 06:29:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/567&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/567&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
